WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
Aotearoa, kaitiakitanga, mana whenua.

2
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Thank you.

3
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.060
you

4
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:57.519
and Michael Kilkalli joining us. Karen, we have 10 minutes with you this morning.

5
00:01:57.519 --> 00:01:59.519
That includes time for questions.

6
00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:01.519
Pass it over to you now.

7
00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:03.519
Thank you, Maurena Koutou.

8
00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:10.519
We're both members of the National Employment Law Committee of the New Zealand Law Society, Te Kahui Ture o Aotearoa.

9
00:02:10.519 --> 00:02:12.519
I'm a barrister in Wellington.

10
00:02:12.519 --> 00:02:20.519
I've got over 30 years' experience in employment law, which covers two holidays acts and two decades in large law firms.

11
00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:27.520
And Michael is an associate with Meredith Connell in Auckland and prior to that he was a judge's clerk in the Employment Court in Auckland.

12
00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:35.520
The approach taken by the New Zealand Law Society when commenting on proposed legislation is a neutral one in terms of policy.

13
00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:43.520
So we're seeking to provide you with feedback on the workability of the legislation, identifying potential issues and drafting.

14
00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:51.520
And as law is our natural view, our natural review mechanism is to think about how we might explain it to our clients.

15
00:02:51.520 --> 00:03:05.520
Our written submission makes a number of comments that are directed to the predictability and certainty of the proposed legislation, but we'll focus only on three of those points today and then leave a few minutes for questions from you.

16
00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:09.520
So I'll start with a standard hours point that we make in our submission.

17
00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:16.520
The bill is premised on standard hours being specified in an employment agreement, roster or notional roster.

18
00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:24.520
And that's the baseline or foundation for annual leave, public holidays, bereavement leave, sick leave, domestic violence leave, et cetera.

19
00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:28.520
So it's really important as a concept in this draft legislation.

20
00:03:28.520 --> 00:03:36.520
So just to start with a practical issue, at the moment, standard hours isn't required in employment agreements.

21
00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:47.520
The employment relations that brings in more flexibility than that and it refers to a requirement to include an indication of the arrangements relating to the times the employer is to work.

22
00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:53.520
So you see some quite flexible and fluid clauses at the moment in employment agreements.

23
00:03:53.520 --> 00:04:05.520
So there's going to be some transition needed if we go with a standard hours notion from what currently is quite flexible and where many employment agreements won't have standard or set hours specified.

24
00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.520
And it's not quite clear how that transition is going to be addressed.

25
00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:21.519
This leads to the second issue about standard hours, which is the bill requires that but doesn't provide a fallback mechanism if the hours aren't specified in any of those ways.

26
00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:28.519
So where the employer and employee simply don't agree and they stick with their current employment agreement, what happens then?

27
00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:33.519
The third issue is whether the standard hours truly reflect what the employee works.

28
00:04:33.519 --> 00:04:44.519
And I listened earlier this morning to some of the industry submissions which have explained the implication of that for how the time off part of leave is calculated.

29
00:04:44.519 --> 00:04:47.519
For the Law Society, our concern is two-fold.

30
00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:51.519
First is that the standard hours might not reflect the current reality.

31
00:04:51.519 --> 00:05:05.519
But second, the shall we say less honourable employers might deliberately set low standard hours knowing that the employees will happily, voluntarily work additional hours in order to boost their pay to that point.

32
00:05:05.519 --> 00:05:13.519
But that means they don't have annual leave and the other actual time off entitlements that accrue at the rate that they're actually working.

33
00:05:14.519 --> 00:05:23.519
The second point I'm going to touch on is what we colloquially know as time and a half for payment on public holidays.

34
00:05:23.519 --> 00:05:28.519
If I can be frank, the clause relating to that one, two, four, it's quite long.

35
00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:36.519
It has cross references in itself and references between some clauses that are quite difficult to follow.

36
00:05:36.519 --> 00:05:43.519
It's one of those clauses that you read and you wonder how you might actually explain that to anybody in terms of how it's meant to work.

37
00:05:43.519 --> 00:05:50.519
So it is complicated. The second point about it is that there are two mechanisms for the time and a half.

38
00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:57.519
So there's one for time and that's what the employer is required to pay the employee for each hour worked.

39
00:05:57.519 --> 00:06:06.519
And then the half has a different calculation and that's greater of 50% of the employee's ordinary hourly rate and any identifiable amount.

40
00:06:06.519 --> 00:06:12.519
So you're doing one calculation for the time and then another one for the half and by no means a payroll expert,

41
00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:19.519
but I think that's going to complicate things as people try to put this in practice.

42
00:06:19.519 --> 00:06:27.519
So those calculation parts might not be the same, which risks the calculations being very complex to do.

43
00:06:27.519 --> 00:06:34.519
So I'll hand over to Michael now to talk about our final point, which is the remediation issue.

44
00:06:34.519 --> 00:06:37.519
Thank you, Karen, and good morning everyone.

45
00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:45.519
So I'm just going to speak to you briefly about the proposed remediation process for outstanding liabilities under the Holidays Act

46
00:06:45.519 --> 00:06:50.519
and those provisions are at Clause 156 in Schedule 3 of the bill.

47
00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:57.519
It's proposed that that process will have retrospective effect and could be used to remediate underpayments and payment failures,

48
00:06:57.519 --> 00:07:03.519
which for whatever reason have occurred up to four years prior to the bill receiving the Royal Ascent.

49
00:07:03.519 --> 00:07:10.519
We're concerned that the material relating to the bill does not discuss whether the retrospective provisions are appropriate.

50
00:07:10.519 --> 00:07:18.519
There does not seem to be any consideration of whether retrospectivity can adversely impact either employers or employees,

51
00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:24.519
for example by reducing or extinguishing some employee's statutory entitlements.

52
00:07:24.519 --> 00:07:30.519
Second, whether the extent of the retrospectivity is appropriate or if it requires adjustment.

53
00:07:30.519 --> 00:07:38.519
And third, whether this process could upset or lead to relitigation of settled matters.

54
00:07:38.519 --> 00:07:48.519
We also have concerns as to whether it is appropriate to prescribe the substantive content of those retrospective provisions through regulations,

55
00:07:48.519 --> 00:07:57.519
rather than through primary legislation, because regulations would not be subject to the same level of public and parliamentary scrutiny.

56
00:07:57.519 --> 00:08:05.519
Those concerns are heightened as the bill does not require the Minister to undertake public consultation on the draft regulations

57
00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:10.519
in circumstances where statutory entitlements are impacted.

58
00:08:10.519 --> 00:08:21.519
Finally, we have concerns about regulations that would specify a minimum amount payable, a term that is in that undefined category that I just spoke about,

59
00:08:21.519 --> 00:08:30.519
would be defined through the regulations, because the regulations would not be subject to the same level of parliamentary and public scrutiny.

60
00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:37.519
This would mean an employer would not be required to make a remediation payment to an employee whose entitlement is below this threshold.

61
00:08:37.519 --> 00:08:43.519
It raises fairness concerns as the threshold could bar an employee from receiving a payment.

62
00:08:43.519 --> 00:08:47.519
They are otherwise entitled to receive, no matter how small the amount.

63
00:08:47.519 --> 00:08:54.519
Those concerns are heightened because we do not know at what level that threshold will be set or how it will be calculated.

64
00:08:54.519 --> 00:08:58.519
A similar concern arises around the concept of reasonable compensation,

65
00:08:58.519 --> 00:09:04.519
given that also appears to contemplate something less than their existing statutory entitlements.

66
00:09:04.519 --> 00:09:13.519
We advise you to seek advice on those matters and to consider whether amendments are necessary to address those concerns.

67
00:09:13.519 --> 00:09:16.519
I'll hand over four questions if there's any time.

68
00:09:16.519 --> 00:09:22.519
Thank you very much. We do have a short amount of time, but we do have one question.

69
00:09:22.519 --> 00:09:25.519
That doesn't appear we have any. We have a question from Jan Taniti.

70
00:09:25.519 --> 00:09:30.519
Thank you Madam Chair, and thank you very much for your submission.

71
00:09:30.519 --> 00:09:38.519
It kind of backs up in many respects what some of the industry bodies have been saying as you said.

72
00:09:38.519 --> 00:09:48.519
One thing I want to get there, you talked about if there is not-so-savory employers as such and what they might do in this situation.

73
00:09:48.519 --> 00:09:53.519
Put it in simple terms, and I'm trying to get my head around this too.

74
00:09:53.519 --> 00:10:01.519
Does that mean that they could be incentivising part-time and casualisation workers in this particular case?

75
00:10:01.519 --> 00:10:06.519
Because it could mean that they're paying out less in the annual leave?

76
00:10:06.519 --> 00:10:10.519
To answer that vaguely, yes, possibly.

77
00:10:10.519 --> 00:10:18.519
But also you could have full-time employees who are put on say 35 or 30 hours a week.

78
00:10:18.519 --> 00:10:22.519
I mean it may be that you're thinking of that as part-time, which is probably right.

79
00:10:22.519 --> 00:10:30.519
But work greater hours than that. So they might say work-have the standard hours of 30 or 35 in their agreement,

80
00:10:30.519 --> 00:10:35.519
but work much more than that on a regular basis.

81
00:10:36.519 --> 00:10:45.519
I think there is a possibility of some, and I'm hesitating to use this word, but some abuse of the system,

82
00:10:45.519 --> 00:10:51.519
particularly by unscrupulous employers who are trying to limit how much time off people actually have,

83
00:10:51.519 --> 00:10:55.519
particularly if they have to bring in replacement employees at a higher cost.

84
00:10:55.519 --> 00:10:59.519
Great, thank you. Thank you for that. And a question from Lauren Tsunan.

85
00:10:59.519 --> 00:11:04.519
Thank you, Madam Chair. Just a very quick question regarding the standard hours as well.

86
00:11:04.519 --> 00:11:15.519
Do you have any data or would this be an understanding of the current average hours that employees actually worked a week?

87
00:11:15.519 --> 00:11:20.519
And potentially is it greater than the standard hours that we're seeing now?

88
00:11:20.519 --> 00:11:24.519
The reason I ask this question is, you know, we hear anecdotally,

89
00:11:24.519 --> 00:11:29.519
but I want to check if there's any data to say that people are working longer and longer hours

90
00:11:29.519 --> 00:11:35.519
that are unseen or unaccounted for in their contract.

91
00:11:35.519 --> 00:11:41.519
That's not data that the law society would hold, so the answer to your question is no, we don't have that data.

92
00:11:41.519 --> 00:11:47.519
It might be held by the Victoria University Employment Relations Centre.

93
00:11:47.519 --> 00:11:51.519
They do an annual analysis of collective agreements and what provisions are in those.

94
00:11:51.519 --> 00:11:54.519
So the data may be somewhere, but it's not held by us, I'm afraid.

95
00:11:54.519 --> 00:11:58.519
Thank you. We might look into that. Thank you so much.

96
00:11:59.519 --> 00:12:03.519
All right. Thank you very much. We appreciate your participation in the process.

97
00:12:03.519 --> 00:12:08.519
You're very constructive and helpful as a mission. So thank you again.

98
00:12:08.519 --> 00:12:09.519
Thank you.

99
00:12:09.519 --> 00:12:13.519
On now to have a similar theme, Simpson-Greason.

100
00:12:13.519 --> 00:12:19.519
We have Rachel Judge and Mike Mercer joining us.

101
00:12:19.519 --> 00:12:27.519
Rachel and Mike, we have 10 minutes with you this morning, and that includes time for questions.

102
00:12:27.519 --> 00:12:29.519
Thank you.

103
00:12:29.519 --> 00:12:35.519
I am Rachel Judge, a partner at Simpson-Greason, and I'm presenting with my colleague, Mike Mercer,

104
00:12:35.519 --> 00:12:41.519
Senior Associate. We have both been heavily involved in advising on the current

105
00:12:41.519 --> 00:12:46.519
Holidays Act and assisting clients through their remediation processes.

106
00:12:46.519 --> 00:12:52.519
And we thank you for the opportunity to present our oral submission today on behalf of Simpson-Greason.

107
00:12:52.519 --> 00:12:59.519
The submission has been informed by feedback from a number of our clients and also in line

108
00:12:59.519 --> 00:13:06.519
with what Karen's just spoken to, our own observations as lawyers as to where complexities may arise

109
00:13:06.519 --> 00:13:09.519
based on the wording of the current bill.

110
00:13:09.519 --> 00:13:15.519
At the outset, I do want to note that Simpson-Greason supports the core objectives of the bill.

111
00:13:15.519 --> 00:13:21.519
We have been actively advocating for many of these changes for a number of years,

112
00:13:21.519 --> 00:13:29.519
in particular the move to an hours-based accrual model and the simplification of leave payment calculations.

113
00:13:29.519 --> 00:13:37.519
That said, there are some aspects of the bill that are likely to pose some compliance issues for employers

114
00:13:37.519 --> 00:13:40.519
and particularly those with complex workforces.

115
00:13:40.519 --> 00:13:48.519
So we do consider that there is room for the bill to potentially include some options to address some of those issues.

116
00:13:48.519 --> 00:13:55.519
And we wish to comment on three key issues from our written submissions where we have made recommendations.

117
00:13:55.519 --> 00:14:05.519
Those are the notional roster, the mandatory standard hours versus additional hours leave compensation payment approach,

118
00:14:05.519 --> 00:14:12.519
which we'll refer to as LCP, and the issue of strike action during the transitional period.

119
00:14:12.519 --> 00:14:17.519
So just turning to the notional roster framework to start with,

120
00:14:17.519 --> 00:14:26.519
this applies to determined leave entitlements where an employee's standard hours or days of work cannot be readily identified.

121
00:14:26.519 --> 00:14:36.519
And while the policy intent is understood, we submit that the framework as drafted may not be workable in practice for many employers.

122
00:14:36.519 --> 00:14:44.519
Clause 9, for example, requires that a notional roster is agreed in writing and kept up to date

123
00:14:44.519 --> 00:14:52.519
in workplaces where hours are variable or changed frequently, that will be difficult if not impossible to apply.

124
00:14:52.519 --> 00:15:00.519
The combination of a requirement for agreement and then continual updating risks, continuous negotiation,

125
00:15:00.519 --> 00:15:08.519
creating significant administrative burden and also employee relations issues flowing from all of that.

126
00:15:08.519 --> 00:15:15.519
For large employers and particularly those with unionized workforces, this is unlikely to be practicable.

127
00:15:15.519 --> 00:15:24.519
There is also a level of uncertainty in the role a notional roster is intended to play, although it's described as notional.

128
00:15:24.519 --> 00:15:33.519
The provisions do require it to reflect actual working patterns to a certain extent and to be revised as those patterns change.

129
00:15:33.519 --> 00:15:42.519
So this risks blurring the distinction between a genuine notional construct and an operational roster and, in our view,

130
00:15:42.519 --> 00:15:48.519
risks undermining the purpose of introducing a simplified mechanism in the first place.

131
00:15:48.519 --> 00:15:58.519
We recognize that there is provision at clauses 10 and 11 for a Labour Inspector to determine a notional roster where agreement cannot be reached,

132
00:15:58.519 --> 00:16:10.519
but we consider that reliance on Labour Inspector determinations as the sole fallback is likely to result in increased disputes, delay and litigation.

133
00:16:10.519 --> 00:16:19.519
So on this point we submit that the framework would be materially improved by introducing an express alternative mechanism

134
00:16:19.519 --> 00:16:29.519
where clause 9 could be amended to provide that where it is not reasonably practicable for an employer and employee to agree a notional roster,

135
00:16:29.519 --> 00:16:36.519
that agreement is not required as a precondition to determining those standard hours for leave purposes

136
00:16:36.519 --> 00:16:47.519
and in line with that that clause 10 is amended to allow an employer without Labour Inspector intervention to determine a notional roster

137
00:16:47.519 --> 00:16:55.519
by applying some form of agreed averaging method and we're hearing from our clients that if some form of rolling average

138
00:16:55.519 --> 00:17:03.519
were applied such as the 13 week average that that's something that could be workable for them going forward.

139
00:17:03.519 --> 00:17:10.519
I'll now hand over to Mike Mercer to discuss the further two points we wanted to raise.

140
00:17:10.519 --> 00:17:12.519
Thank you, Rachel.

141
00:17:13.519 --> 00:17:23.519
Further, the two points I want to speak to, the first relates to the lead compensation approach and like our learner friends from the New Zealand Law Society,

142
00:17:23.519 --> 00:17:29.519
we addressed the mechanism for additional hours being paid by the lead compensation payment.

143
00:17:29.519 --> 00:17:35.519
While we understand this is intended to provide certainty and to avoid the accumulation of large leave liabilities,

144
00:17:35.519 --> 00:17:44.519
there are two circumstances where hours of work will fluctuate and it could create some outcomes for an employer that are not consistent with the bill

145
00:17:44.519 --> 00:17:53.519
and operational difficulties. In particular, the structure of the lead compensation payment will create incentive for employees to favour being paid

146
00:17:53.519 --> 00:17:59.519
in a cash loading rather than accruing leave and the resist agreement to standard hours.

147
00:17:59.519 --> 00:18:09.519
What we're hearing from clients who are really concerned about their ability to agree with standard hours with their employees is that given the attractiveness of lead compensation payment,

148
00:18:09.519 --> 00:18:22.519
you could end up in a situation that is different from what has been discussed previously with actually employees all time including who would prefer to end up on low standard hours with large additional hours

149
00:18:22.519 --> 00:18:30.519
that would provide the disincentive to them taking sick leave when needed and significantly receive their reduced pay when they do so.

150
00:18:30.519 --> 00:18:37.519
The bill doesn't currently allow for alternative approaches that may reduce the same or better outcome for employees.

151
00:18:37.519 --> 00:18:50.519
In practice, we are hearing from clients who have a strong preference to accrue leave on all hours work including additional hours while others may prefer the pay-as-you-go model of the lead compensation payment.

152
00:18:50.519 --> 00:18:58.519
Either approach would be broadly neutral and effective for employees that have a get-leave paid at the time or the ability to take it later.

153
00:18:58.519 --> 00:19:08.519
In our view, there is scope to deliver on the intent of the bill for allowing greater flexibility in how lead entitlements are delivered without jeopardising employee protections or entitlements.

154
00:19:08.519 --> 00:19:27.519
We therefore recommend that clauses 129 and 132 of the bill be amended to allow employers as an alternative to paying lead compensation on additional hours to accrue leave on all hours work in addition including those additional hours at their election.

155
00:19:27.519 --> 00:19:32.519
The second point we wish to raise relates to strike action during the transitional period.

156
00:19:32.519 --> 00:19:45.519
It is inevitable that there will be areas of disagreement during the transition process given the new lead framework will require significant changes to existing employment agreements, payroll systems and operational practices.

157
00:19:45.519 --> 00:19:56.519
We are concerned that without clear limits, disputes arising solely from the application of the transitional provisions may become the subject of strike action or lockouts.

158
00:19:56.519 --> 00:20:11.519
There is precedent that unions and employees cannot participate in unlawful industrial action even when it otherwise relates to bargaining if the issue in dispute arises from a legislatively defined process by way of example.

159
00:20:11.519 --> 00:20:22.519
The Fair Pay Agreements Act in 2022 which has since been repealed included expressed restrictions on industrial action in relation to fair pay bargaining.

160
00:20:23.519 --> 00:20:35.519
We therefore recommend that the bill be amended to provide that disputes arising solely from the application or operation of the transitional provisions cannot be subject to industrial action during the transitional period.

161
00:20:35.519 --> 00:20:50.519
This could be achieved by adopting a similar approach to that in the All My Fair Pay Agreement Act and in this context disagreements about the conversion, reconciliation or technical application of the transition rules should be treated as procedural matters

162
00:20:50.519 --> 00:20:58.519
and resolved from interpretation, guidance or dispute resolves and mechanisms via the employment institutions rather than industrial action.

163
00:20:58.519 --> 00:21:01.519
Thank you Madam Chair and members of the select committee.

164
00:21:01.519 --> 00:21:04.519
We are prepared to take any questions at this time.

165
00:21:04.519 --> 00:21:12.519
We have one minute and I doesn't appear that we do and can I just say it's not a reflection of the lack of interest.

166
00:21:12.519 --> 00:21:13.519
I have to make that very clear.

167
00:21:13.519 --> 00:21:18.519
You always put forward incredibly comprehensive and helpful submission and I thank you for that.

168
00:21:18.519 --> 00:21:21.519
And I know that our officials would thank you for that too.

169
00:21:21.519 --> 00:21:22.519
Thank you.

170
00:21:22.519 --> 00:21:23.519
Very good.

171
00:21:23.519 --> 00:21:24.519
Thank you.

172
00:21:24.519 --> 00:21:25.519
So we'll move on now to our next submitter.

173
00:21:25.519 --> 00:21:26.519
Thank you.

174
00:21:26.519 --> 00:21:27.519
Thank you.

175
00:21:27.519 --> 00:21:29.519
We have Madfly Limited Trading.

176
00:21:29.519 --> 00:21:31.519
We have Sherilyn Walther.

177
00:21:31.519 --> 00:21:38.519
Hopefully I'm pronouncing your surname correctly.

178
00:21:38.519 --> 00:21:47.519
Enterprise and Staffing Innovations New Zealand if that makes more sense to you.

179
00:21:48.519 --> 00:21:49.519
Apologies.

180
00:21:49.519 --> 00:21:50.519
Having a few technical issues there.

181
00:21:50.519 --> 00:21:51.519
I hope you can have me.

182
00:21:51.519 --> 00:21:52.519
That's okay.

183
00:21:52.519 --> 00:21:53.519
Easy.

184
00:21:53.519 --> 00:21:54.519
You've got to have me.

185
00:21:54.519 --> 00:21:55.519
Right.

186
00:21:55.519 --> 00:21:56.519
Sorry.

187
00:21:56.519 --> 00:21:57.519
Apology.

188
00:21:57.519 --> 00:21:58.519
Sorry.

189
00:21:58.519 --> 00:21:59.519
Let's just get that right.

190
00:21:59.519 --> 00:22:00.519
I haven't seen your logo.

191
00:22:00.519 --> 00:22:01.519
Sorry.

192
00:22:01.519 --> 00:22:03.519
It is actually a trading name of Madfly Limited.

193
00:22:03.519 --> 00:22:05.519
So thank you Madam Chairman and members of the committee.

194
00:22:05.519 --> 00:22:12.519
Thank you for the opportunity to appear today and speak to EZNZ's written submission on the Employment Leave Bill.

195
00:22:12.519 --> 00:22:17.519
My name is Sherilyn Walther and I'm the Managing Director appearing on behalf of Enterprise and Staffing Innovations NZ.

196
00:22:17.519 --> 00:22:20.519
My name is Sherilyn Walther, otherwise known as EZNZ.

197
00:22:20.519 --> 00:22:27.519
By way of background, EZNZ provides practical employment relations and HR support to businesses across New Zealand.

198
00:22:27.519 --> 00:22:33.519
A big part of our work is helping clients with the operational employment issues that come up every day in real workplaces.

199
00:22:33.519 --> 00:22:38.519
Things like leave, payroll, payroll interpretation, rostering process and documentation.

200
00:22:38.519 --> 00:22:45.519
These are matters that can look quite straightforward on paper but if they're handled incorrectly, they can very quickly turn into disputes.

201
00:22:45.519 --> 00:22:49.519
The condition of our clients is small to medium sized businesses.

202
00:22:49.519 --> 00:22:53.519
For those businesses, getting employment processes wrong is not just frustrating.

203
00:22:53.519 --> 00:22:56.519
It's expensive, distracting and disruptive.

204
00:22:56.519 --> 00:23:01.519
Most do not have in-house legal teams or large HR functions, if at all.

205
00:23:01.519 --> 00:23:06.519
They're trying to do the right thing but they need the law to be clear and they need it to be workable.

206
00:23:06.519 --> 00:23:14.519
When disputes do arise, even a claim with little or no merit can still cost up to $10,000 to defend

207
00:23:14.519 --> 00:23:18.519
and costs alone before you factor in management time stress and disruption to the business.

208
00:23:18.519 --> 00:23:22.519
So from our perspective, clarity and employment legislation really matters.

209
00:23:22.519 --> 00:23:28.519
If the law is too technical, too uncertain or too hard to apply in day-to-day operations, the consequences are very real.

210
00:23:28.519 --> 00:23:36.519
With that in mind, our overall position on this is that we support the direction of reform but we say the bill still needs refinement.

211
00:23:36.519 --> 00:23:38.519
We support the objective behind the bill.

212
00:23:38.519 --> 00:23:41.519
The current leave framework is too complicated.

213
00:23:41.519 --> 00:23:46.519
It's been difficult for employers to understand and difficult for payroll systems to properly apply.

214
00:23:46.519 --> 00:23:50.519
And it's led to too many errors and too much uncertainty so reform is needed.

215
00:23:50.519 --> 00:23:54.519
We support the intention of creating a simpler and clearer leave system.

216
00:23:54.519 --> 00:24:02.519
But our key message today is that simplification should not come at the cost of fairness, operational workability or new compliance risks.

217
00:24:02.519 --> 00:24:07.519
In our view, the bill makes some very positive changes but there are still several areas where it needs tightening

218
00:24:07.519 --> 00:24:11.519
so it does not simply replace one set of problems with another.

219
00:24:11.519 --> 00:24:14.519
So there are parts of the bill that we clearly support.

220
00:24:14.519 --> 00:24:17.519
We support prorated sick leave occurring from the first day of employment.

221
00:24:17.519 --> 00:24:21.519
That's easier to understand and it better reflects service over time.

222
00:24:21.519 --> 00:24:23.519
We support annual leave occurring from day one.

223
00:24:23.519 --> 00:24:30.519
That's much easier to explain than the current distinction between a crude leave and annual leave becoming available only after 12 months.

224
00:24:30.519 --> 00:24:34.519
And we support clearer rules around public holidays and otherwise working days.

225
00:24:34.519 --> 00:24:39.519
But the clarity in the area should reduce uncertainty and reduce the risk of underpayment issues.

226
00:24:39.519 --> 00:24:43.519
So this is not a submission opposing reform, quite the opposite.

227
00:24:43.519 --> 00:24:48.519
We support reform. We just want to make sure the reform is genuinely workable in practice.

228
00:24:48.519 --> 00:24:55.519
Our biggest concern is the 12.5% leave compensation payment for hours above minimum contracted hours.

229
00:24:55.519 --> 00:24:58.519
This is probably our most significant concern.

230
00:24:58.519 --> 00:25:05.519
We're concerned about the proposal to require a leave compensation payment of at least 12.5% for additional hours and casual hours.

231
00:25:05.519 --> 00:25:14.519
That may appear simple at a high level but in practice it creates real problems for businesses where workers have genuine ongoing employment and regular patterns of work

232
00:25:14.519 --> 00:25:17.519
but may work more than they guaranteed minimum hours.

233
00:25:17.519 --> 00:25:21.519
This is a very common arrangement especially in small to medium businesses.

234
00:25:21.519 --> 00:25:27.519
In many cases businesses will guarantee for example 30 hours a week but regularly offer more.

235
00:25:27.519 --> 00:25:29.519
The reason for that is practical.

236
00:25:29.519 --> 00:25:38.519
In sectors such as agriculture and construction the amount of work available is often heavily dependent on weather conditions and changing operational demands.

237
00:25:38.519 --> 00:25:46.519
Businesses are trying to provide employees with a reliable minimum while still retaining the flexibility to offer more hours when conditions allow.

238
00:25:46.519 --> 00:25:52.519
So a person may be contracted for 30 hours but often work 40 when the weather is favorable and work can proceed.

239
00:25:52.519 --> 00:25:57.519
This is like construction that could actually be even more so you might work more hours in the summer than you do in the winter.

240
00:25:57.519 --> 00:26:02.519
That does not make them casual in the ordinary sense.

241
00:26:02.519 --> 00:26:10.519
Our concern is that if every hour above guaranteed minimum automatically attracts a 12.5% leave payment that creates a number of problems.

242
00:26:10.519 --> 00:26:13.519
So it creates more payroll complexity, not less.

243
00:26:13.519 --> 00:26:16.519
It increases labour cost immediately.

244
00:26:16.519 --> 00:26:20.519
It may reduce the employee's ability to build up meaningful paid leave over time

245
00:26:20.519 --> 00:26:27.519
and it may encourage a system where leave is effectively cashed out as work happens instead of being preserved as time away from work.

246
00:26:27.519 --> 00:26:32.519
From our perspective that's not just a payroll issue, it's also a well-being issue.

247
00:26:32.519 --> 00:26:41.519
So our recommendation is that the bill should draw a clearer distinction between genuine casual work and ordinary additional hours worked in ongoing employment.

248
00:26:41.519 --> 00:26:49.519
Where there is a real ongoing employment there should be a pathway for leave to recruit rather than requiring automatic pay as you go treatment.

249
00:26:49.519 --> 00:26:55.519
So the bill also needs to be clearer and more practical treatment of casual employment.

250
00:26:55.519 --> 00:27:00.519
Closely linked to the 12.5% leave compensation payment is the question of casual work.

251
00:27:00.519 --> 00:27:07.519
One of the real issues for employers is knowing when a worker who starts out as a casual has in reality become regular.

252
00:27:07.519 --> 00:27:13.519
That matters because it affects payroll treatment, leave treatment, legal risks and fairness.

253
00:27:13.519 --> 00:27:23.519
If the bill is going to rely on a separate model for casual employees then it needs to be much clearer about when someone is genuinely casual and when they're no longer casual.

254
00:27:23.519 --> 00:27:27.519
Otherwise we're just creating a new uncertainty in place of an old one.

255
00:27:27.519 --> 00:27:39.519
So our recommendation is that the bill include either a clearer statutory test or a review point so that where work becomes regular and predictable the employee moves into the ordinary accrual work-frame or framework.

256
00:27:40.519 --> 00:27:45.519
The bill should also avoid creating unfairness between casual and permanent workers.

257
00:27:45.519 --> 00:27:47.519
We're also concerned about parity on this one.

258
00:27:47.519 --> 00:28:00.519
If a casual worker receives 12.5% upfront but a permanent worker accrues leave that only becomes valuable when it's actually taken then there's a real possibility of inequitable outcomes between different categories of workers.

259
00:28:00.519 --> 00:28:04.519
We're not suggesting casual workers should be disadvantaged, that's not our point.

260
00:28:04.519 --> 00:28:10.519
Our point is that simplification should still produce fair outcomes across the workforce.

261
00:28:10.519 --> 00:28:19.519
The committee should test carefully whether the structure of the bill creates unintended imbalance between workers who may be doing similar work but under different employment arrangements.

262
00:28:21.519 --> 00:28:25.519
So next we have KiwiSaver and Commission need to be expressly clarified.

263
00:28:25.519 --> 00:28:29.519
We also think the bill should be clearer on some points around the remuneration issues.

264
00:28:29.519 --> 00:28:31.519
The first is KiwiSaver.

265
00:28:31.519 --> 00:28:37.519
The treatment of KiwiSaver in relation to leave compensation payments should be set out clearly in the legislation.

266
00:28:37.519 --> 00:28:46.519
If it's not employers and payroll providers will take different approaches and that inconsistency will create exactly the kind of confusion this reform is trying to fix.

267
00:28:46.519 --> 00:28:50.519
The second is commission and nondiscretionary incentive payments.

268
00:28:50.519 --> 00:29:00.519
A simpler leave model should not result in regular commission income being left out of leave calculations where that income is a normal part of the employee's earnings.

269
00:29:00.519 --> 00:29:10.519
If that happens, employees in commission based or incentive based roles may end up worse off when taking leave and that creates a real disincentive to take and leave at all.

270
00:29:10.519 --> 00:29:16.519
That would be an unfair outcome and would undermine the broader purpose of leave entitlements.

271
00:29:16.519 --> 00:29:26.519
So we say the bill should expressly preserve the inclusion of regular nondiscretionary payment and similar payments or provide a mechanism that properly captures them.

272
00:29:26.519 --> 00:29:32.519
The variable hour work is still not fully resolved especially around day based leave and notional rosters.

273
00:29:32.519 --> 00:29:40.519
Our final point is that the bill does not yet fully resolve the practical issues that arise for workers with variable hours and variable days.

274
00:29:40.519 --> 00:29:46.519
We remain concerned about day based leave, particularly bereavement leave and family violence leave.

275
00:29:46.519 --> 00:29:55.519
Where people do not work the same pattern each week there can be uncertainty about what counts as a day, how part days should be treated and how leaves should apply across changing rosters.

276
00:29:55.519 --> 00:29:59.519
We're also concerned about notional rosters.

277
00:29:59.519 --> 00:30:08.519
At the moment the bill does not seem to give enough practical certainty about when a notional roster is required, what information is needed to create one and when it should be reviewed.

278
00:30:08.519 --> 00:30:15.519
Without that clarity there's a real risk of more inconsistency, more confusion and ultimately more disputes.

279
00:30:15.519 --> 00:30:25.519
At the very least we think that the legislation or supporting regulations should include clearer guidance and practical worked examples before the bill comes into force.

280
00:30:25.519 --> 00:30:28.519
So in closing our message is a straightforward one.

281
00:30:28.519 --> 00:30:30.519
We support the goal of this bill.

282
00:30:30.519 --> 00:30:33.519
We support day one accrual for sick leave and annual leave.

283
00:30:33.519 --> 00:30:35.519
And we support clearer public holiday rules.

284
00:30:35.519 --> 00:30:41.519
But we ask the committee to refine the bill so it does not simplify shift complexity from one part of the system to another.

285
00:30:41.519 --> 00:30:45.519
Sorry it does not simply shift complexity, sorry.

286
00:30:45.519 --> 00:30:54.519
In particular we ask the committee to look carefully at the 12.5% leave compensation rule, the treatment of casual work, fairness between casual and permanent workers,

287
00:30:54.519 --> 00:31:02.519
key we save a treatment, commission and incentive payments and the practical operation of day based leave and notional rosters.

288
00:31:02.519 --> 00:31:08.519
If these areas are improved we think the bill will be stronger, fairer and much more workable in the real world.

289
00:31:08.519 --> 00:31:12.519
Thank you for your time and I'm happy to answer questions if you've got time.

290
00:31:12.519 --> 00:31:14.519
Thank you very much Sherilyn.

291
00:31:14.519 --> 00:31:19.519
We do believe and I think we've run out of time with you we have unfortunately.

292
00:31:19.519 --> 00:31:25.519
But thank you so much for being part of this process and I've got to say a really good submission, really helpful.

293
00:31:25.519 --> 00:31:32.519
And I assume and assure you sorry that the officials will be pleased too.

294
00:31:32.519 --> 00:31:34.519
Thank you very much.

