00:42:27.519 --> 00:42:34.519
And the history of the last few years has been full of many thousands of hours, many thousands,

405
00:42:34.519 --> 00:42:39.519
many hundreds of thousands of dollars of cost in terms of remediating and getting agreement to processes.

406
00:42:39.519 --> 00:42:45.519
What we would rather see, perhaps, is rather than have a schedule come into effect in two years' time

407
00:42:45.519 --> 00:42:50.519
and regulations that can be developed at any time from the native ascent,

408
00:42:50.519 --> 00:42:54.519
is to put it all together and say, why don't we have the process and the criteria

409
00:42:54.519 --> 00:42:58.519
able to be developed together and as soon as they're available, they can be used.

410
00:42:58.519 --> 00:43:01.519
That would be the first element of our suggestion.

411
00:43:01.519 --> 00:43:09.519
But the second is, as it stands in the bill, the process effectively allows the employer to choose to use the process

412
00:43:09.519 --> 00:43:13.519
and without the permission of the employers who would be affected by it.

413
00:43:13.519 --> 00:43:19.519
That has some potential ramifications, particularly in relation to the Wages Protection Act,

414
00:43:19.519 --> 00:43:26.519
because it seems to us that an employee whose pay has not been correctly determined under the current act

415
00:43:26.519 --> 00:43:30.519
is, as it is now, currently entitled to have that put right.

416
00:43:30.519 --> 00:43:35.519
And yet the remediation process, as we heard from an earlier submitter,

417
00:43:35.519 --> 00:43:42.519
may contain elements that have an averaging or a near enough, good enough answer to it,

418
00:43:42.519 --> 00:43:46.519
which may in fact leave that employee short of what they would otherwise get

419
00:43:46.519 --> 00:43:49.519
if they were properly remediated under the current act.

420
00:43:49.519 --> 00:43:54.519
So we think, and there's no mention of the Wages Protection Act in relation to this,

421
00:43:54.519 --> 00:44:01.519
so there's a potential point to be checked, and it's up to officials to have a look at that,

422
00:44:01.519 --> 00:44:06.519
but we would rather see a process that was developed together in its entirety

423
00:44:06.519 --> 00:44:10.519
so that proper consultation could be undertaken over the development of that process

424
00:44:10.519 --> 00:44:12.519
and through the regulatory process.

425
00:44:12.519 --> 00:44:18.519
And also that the use of it is one that has the employers engaged with it as well

426
00:44:18.519 --> 00:44:21.519
so that they can see that what they're being offered is fair,

427
00:44:21.519 --> 00:44:25.519
and the whole process becomes together as one rather than being in two parts.

428
00:44:25.519 --> 00:44:28.519
So that's remediation as far as we're concerned.

429
00:44:28.519 --> 00:44:30.519
We think that would benefit.

430
00:44:30.519 --> 00:44:37.519
We've also got the issue of, as a number of submitters have made on the leave compensation payment,

431
00:44:37.519 --> 00:44:43.519
but first in relation to rosters, as it stands the bill effectively has a roster

432
00:44:43.519 --> 00:44:48.519
that can contain both standard hours and agreed additional hours.

433
00:44:48.519 --> 00:44:52.519
With the issues that have been raised around the cost of additional hours

434
00:44:52.519 --> 00:44:56.519
and the leave compensation attached to them, we think there's sense,

435
00:44:56.519 --> 00:45:01.519
and most from a payroll point of view, and also a cost and common sense point of view,

436
00:45:01.519 --> 00:45:03.519
that a roster is a roster.

437
00:45:03.519 --> 00:45:06.519
So anything in a roster would be standard hours,

438
00:45:06.519 --> 00:45:10.519
and anything outside a roster would be additional hours.

439
00:45:10.519 --> 00:45:15.519
That, I think, goes a long way to addressing some of the concerns that the law society

440
00:45:15.519 --> 00:45:19.519
and others raised where the cost of additional hours inside a roster,

441
00:45:19.519 --> 00:45:23.519
especially where the rosters are variable, can have quite unforeseen circumstances

442
00:45:23.519 --> 00:45:26.519
or consequences for businesses, certainly additional costs,

443
00:45:26.519 --> 00:45:30.519
and particularly in relation to small businesses, as we heard with the previous submitter,

444
00:45:30.519 --> 00:45:34.519
the variability of costs is one of the things that they confront every day,

445
00:45:34.519 --> 00:45:40.519
simplifying it so that any given roster is known to have a particular cost attached to it

446
00:45:40.519 --> 00:45:43.519
would be of a benefit.

447
00:45:43.519 --> 00:45:49.519
There are a number of other points in our submission which are written down,

448
00:45:49.519 --> 00:45:52.519
